Thanks so much for having me.

17
00:00:50,110 --> 00:00:53,059
So the Chinese Communist Party has vowed to
take over Taiwan

18
00:00:53,059 --> 00:00:55,629
with military force if necessary.

19
00:00:55,629 --> 00:00:59,750
How does that looming shadow sort of affect
Taiwanese politics?

20
00:00:59,750 --> 00:01:03,269
So in Taiwan, when we think about a left-right
spectrum

21
00:01:03,269 --> 00:01:08,460
in the way that we think left-right in say
America, it's very different here.

22
00:01:08,460 --> 00:01:13,420
So in America, we think more along the lines
of tax,

23
00:01:13,420 --> 00:01:15,520
wealth redistribution, welfare, even social
issues

24
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:20,000
like how you feel about things like same sex
marriage, et cetera.

25
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:24,770
In Taiwan, left-right is instead defined by
independence versus unification.

26
00:01:24,770 --> 00:01:28,020
So how Taiwanese people feel about whether
Taiwan ought to become

27
00:01:28,020 --> 00:01:32,610
more sovereign and maybe its own independent
state or less sovereign

28
00:01:32,610 --> 00:01:36,619
and slowly create ties and become a part of
the PRC.

29
00:01:36,619 --> 00:01:39,509
So for Americans who don't really know Taiwanese
politics,

30
00:01:39,509 --> 00:01:43,189
what are the main parties and what are their
views?

31
00:01:43,189 --> 00:01:44,969
So the two biggest parties in Taiwan

32
00:01:44,969 --> 00:01:46,870
are the Democratic Progressive Party,

33
00:01:46,870 --> 00:01:51,280
the DPP and the Chinese Nationalist Party,
the KMT.

34
00:01:51,280 --> 00:01:54,900
Now, Taiwan was under martial law for 37 years.

35
00:01:54,900 --> 00:01:58,740
During that time that came, the KMT was the
only party in Taiwan.

36
00:01:58,740 --> 00:02:03,310
It controlled all aspects of life and other
parties were illegal.

37
00:02:03,310 --> 00:02:06,289
But through a very long struggle of democratization,

38
00:02:06,289 --> 00:02:09,460
eventually a group was able to actually consolidate

39
00:02:09,460 --> 00:02:11,320
their kind of pro-democracy,

40
00:02:11,320 --> 00:02:14,730
[inaudible] KMT political circles and form

41
00:02:14,730 --> 00:02:16,540
what is now known as the DPP,

42
00:02:16,540 --> 00:02:18,620
the Democratic Progressive Party.

43
00:02:18,620 --> 00:02:24,230
Now the DPP is vaguely pro-Taiwan sovereignty.

44
00:02:24,230 --> 00:02:27,420
A lot of people described the DPP as a pro-independence
party,

45
00:02:27,420 --> 00:02:30,810
but in fact the DPP has not been pro-independence
for quite some time,

46
00:02:30,810 --> 00:02:34,060
especially since around the year 2000 the
DPP

47
00:02:34,060 --> 00:02:36,450
has been adamantly pro status quo.

48
00:02:36,450 --> 00:02:39,731
So which is actually why the current president
Tsai Ing-wen

49
00:02:39,731 --> 00:02:42,210
was so controversial,

50
00:02:42,210 --> 00:02:45,000
because she was pushing it further than the
status quo.

51
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,020
No, she actually is explicitly pro status
quo

52
00:02:48,020 --> 00:02:52,730
and a lot of deeper green Taiwanese political
parties don't like her

53
00:02:52,730 --> 00:02:54,390
because she's so pro status quo.

54
00:02:54,390 --> 00:02:55,490
But I thought she wasn't,

55
00:02:55,490 --> 00:02:58,910
she wasn't using the one China policy in speeches.

56
00:02:58,910 --> 00:03:00,520
And I thought that got people's-

57
00:03:00,520 --> 00:03:03,260
No, that doesn't really have a big impact
on

58
00:03:03,260 --> 00:03:04,970
whether or not they're pro status quo or not.

59
00:03:04,970 --> 00:03:06,890
So pro status quo means that they don't want

60
00:03:06,890 --> 00:03:09,510
to change how things are now.

61
00:03:09,510 --> 00:03:10,750
Okay.

62
00:03:10,750 --> 00:03:15,950
Now whether or not she endorses the '92 consensus,

63
00:03:15,950 --> 00:03:19,980
China's one China versus the America's one
China,

64
00:03:19,980 --> 00:03:21,550
these are kind of separate issues from whether
or not

65
00:03:21,550 --> 00:03:26,200
she's actually pushing any sort of actual
change, which she hasn't.

66
00:03:26,200 --> 00:03:31,130
She even just this last week has had to actually
emphasized to the T

67
00:03:31,130 --> 00:03:39,590
that she is a ROC leader, specifically inciting
[inaudible]

68
00:03:39,590 --> 00:03:48,540
as not any sort of pro-Taiwan independence
leaning anything,

69
00:03:48,540 --> 00:03:50,610
which is why when a lot of people say that
Tsai Ing-wen herself

70
00:03:50,610 --> 00:03:53,950
is pro-independence, it's just kind of not
true,

71
00:03:53,950 --> 00:03:57,640
because nothing about her speech or the policy
she's pushes

72
00:03:57,640 --> 00:03:59,440
is really indicative that she's pro-independence.

73
00:03:59,440 --> 00:04:02,730
She's just very pro status quo and that's
not a good thing or a bad thing.

74
00:04:02,730 --> 00:04:03,790
It's just more of a reflection

75
00:04:03,790 --> 00:04:07,690
of how she actually falls within Taiwan's
spectrum.

76
00:04:07,690 --> 00:04:11,720
Now the KMT falls on the more pro-unification
side.

77
00:04:11,720 --> 00:04:14,200
Now, of course, the KMT doesn't just say we're
pro-unification.

78
00:04:14,200 --> 00:04:18,090
Instead, what they do is their strategy

79
00:04:18,090 --> 00:04:21,790
is to try to sell closer ties with China

80
00:04:21,790 --> 00:04:23,290
to the Taiwanese public.

81
00:04:23,290 --> 00:04:25,760
So a lot of their strategy is saying

82
00:04:25,760 --> 00:04:28,620
we can become a more successful Taiwan

83
00:04:28,620 --> 00:04:33,010
if we increase our ties with China.

84
00:04:33,010 --> 00:04:35,040
And of course, they rely on a lot of much
more

85
00:04:35,040 --> 00:04:37,850
kind of essentialist cultural traits

86
00:04:37,850 --> 00:04:40,450
by saying we were both speak Chinese,

87
00:04:40,450 --> 00:04:42,940
we both come from the same ancestors,

88
00:04:42,940 --> 00:04:44,990
therefore we should align with them.

89
00:04:44,990 --> 00:04:46,530
But for a lot of people in Taiwan,

90
00:04:46,530 --> 00:04:48,430
those kinds of appeals don't work anymore,

91
00:04:48,430 --> 00:04:51,190
because Taiwan has politically and culturally
developed

92
00:04:51,190 --> 00:04:55,440
so separately from the PRC for a very, very
long time.

93
00:04:55,440 --> 00:04:59,950
So what is the feeling in Taiwan with this
sort of independence

94
00:04:59,950 --> 00:05:02,450
or unification stance?

95
00:05:02,450 --> 00:05:03,690
Because I would think a lot of...

96
00:05:03,690 --> 00:05:08,740
I don't understand why there’d be people
talking about unification.

97
00:05:08,740 --> 00:05:13,170
So an important, and this gets very complicated,

98
00:05:13,170 --> 00:05:15,620
so within these camps of independence unification,

99
00:05:15,620 --> 00:05:16,870
there is no black and white.

100
00:05:16,870 --> 00:05:19,260
One thing is independence and one thing is
unification.

101
00:05:19,260 --> 00:05:21,170
So within the independence camp,

102
00:05:21,170 --> 00:05:23,570
what independence means is hotly contested.

103
00:05:23,570 --> 00:05:24,570
Okay.

104
00:05:24,570 --> 00:05:25,680
Within the unification camp,

105
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:28,400
what unification means is also contested.

106
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:31,940
So when we ask these kinds of survey questions,

107
00:05:31,940 --> 00:05:33,900
are you pro-independence or pro-unification?

108
00:05:33,900 --> 00:05:36,980
If that's all the question asked, that's not
a very good question.

109
00:05:36,980 --> 00:05:41,440
What's a better question is, should Taiwan
pursue more independence

110
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:44,480
if there is no chance of war with the PRC?

111
00:05:44,480 --> 00:05:48,010
Because when you ask that question, independence
goes up,

112
00:05:48,010 --> 00:05:49,010
are you pro-independence?

113
00:05:49,010 --> 00:05:53,180
If war with the PRC is likely, then it goes
down.

114
00:05:53,180 --> 00:05:56,110
Are you pro-unification if all of China were
to democratize?

115
00:05:56,110 --> 00:05:59,520
Now, it might seem overstated, but if,

116
00:05:59,520 --> 00:06:02,070
if you're okay with unification if China's
also democratic

117
00:06:02,070 --> 00:06:03,580
and those numbers also change.

118
00:06:03,580 --> 00:06:06,220
So one of the ways the Chinese Communist Party

119
00:06:06,220 --> 00:06:08,420
has presented a possible unification scenario

120
00:06:08,420 --> 00:06:10,680
is the one country, two systems.

121
00:06:10,680 --> 00:06:15,770
Sorry all they have in Hong Kong, which is
going very well.

122
00:06:15,770 --> 00:06:20,050
But so a lot of people have been saying since
people in Taiwan,

123
00:06:20,050 --> 00:06:22,389
I've seen how that has gone down in Hong Kong

124
00:06:22,389 --> 00:06:26,910
that's had a big influence in Taiwanese politics.

125
00:06:26,910 --> 00:06:29,650
Do you think there might be something else
going on?

126
00:06:29,650 --> 00:06:30,650
What's going on?

127
00:06:30,650 --> 00:06:33,510
So the way that Hong Kong has impacted Taiwan's
election,

128
00:06:33,510 --> 00:06:35,430
it most certainly has had an impact,

129
00:06:35,430 --> 00:06:38,270
but it has by no means really defined this
election

130
00:06:38,270 --> 00:06:40,300
the way that many people might think.

131
00:06:40,300 --> 00:06:44,800
So what Hong Kong presents to Taiwan is kind
of the same issue

132
00:06:44,800 --> 00:06:46,660
that Taiwan always talks about.

133
00:06:46,660 --> 00:06:51,150
So in Taiwan, every election, the issue of
independence,

134
00:06:51,150 --> 00:06:53,900
unification is the most important political
issue.

135
00:06:53,900 --> 00:06:55,020
That's what people vote on.

136
00:06:55,020 --> 00:06:58,230
That's how people evaluate their candidates
and evaluate their parties.

137
00:06:58,230 --> 00:07:02,770
So in a world where the Hong Kong protests
never occurred,

138
00:07:02,770 --> 00:07:05,300
Taiwan would still be talking about unification,

139
00:07:05,300 --> 00:07:11,170
independence, sovereignty, one country, two
systems just as much.

140
00:07:11,170 --> 00:07:13,840
But what Hong Kong does offer to Taiwan is

141
00:07:13,840 --> 00:07:17,740
a very tangible way of looking at unification.

142
00:07:17,740 --> 00:07:21,740
So we always think about unification, one
country, two systems

143
00:07:21,740 --> 00:07:23,080
in this very abstract way.

144
00:07:23,080 --> 00:07:25,840
And what Hong Kong gives Taiwan is a very
concrete way

145
00:07:25,840 --> 00:07:29,550
to say that's unification and that's why we
shouldn't be for it.

146
00:07:29,550 --> 00:07:34,120
Now, that appeal is very powerful, but for
green voters.

147
00:07:34,120 --> 00:07:38,540
Meaning green, meaning pro-DPP pro-Taiwan
sovereignty voters.

148
00:07:38,540 --> 00:07:41,639
So if you're pro-KMT or you're pro-China,

149
00:07:41,639 --> 00:07:44,150
Hong Kong probably isn't going to have that
big of an effect

150
00:07:44,150 --> 00:07:46,070
on how you're going to vote.

151
00:07:46,070 --> 00:07:50,460
Really when the DPP uses Hong Kong

152
00:07:50,460 --> 00:07:51,980
within their rhetorical strategy,

153
00:07:51,980 --> 00:07:54,650
it's a matter of appealing to young people,

154
00:07:54,650 --> 00:07:57,130
but it's also a matter of trying to get their
base of support

155
00:07:57,130 --> 00:08:01,110
to go out to vote, more than it is trying
to convince,

156
00:08:01,110 --> 00:08:04,590
say moderate or pan-Blue voters to instead
vote for them.

157
00:08:04,590 --> 00:08:07,900
So how are these elections different than
the elections

158
00:08:07,900 --> 00:08:09,990
several years ago in 2016?

159
00:08:09,990 --> 00:08:13,740
So a number of big differences.

160
00:08:13,740 --> 00:08:18,150
So the 2014 Sunflower Movement created this
very dynamic moment

161
00:08:18,150 --> 00:08:20,169
in Taiwanese contemporary history

162
00:08:20,169 --> 00:08:23,010
in which a lot of new political parties

163
00:08:23,010 --> 00:08:26,070
formed out of social activism,

164
00:08:26,070 --> 00:08:28,740
formed and entered formal politics in 2016,

165
00:08:28,740 --> 00:08:30,199
in the last election.

166
00:08:30,199 --> 00:08:32,760
In 2016, there was a lot of hype around these

167
00:08:32,760 --> 00:08:36,419
new young progressive pro-Taiwan parties.

168
00:08:36,419 --> 00:08:37,800
Because of the Sunflower Movement

169
00:08:37,800 --> 00:08:45,010
and eight years of a very unsuccessful Ma
Ying-jeou term president,

170
00:08:45,010 --> 00:08:46,800
presidential term.

171
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:50,440
The kind of sentiment towards the KMT was
at an all time low,

172
00:08:50,440 --> 00:08:54,440
meaning that people were not excited to vote
for the KMT in the last election.

173
00:08:54,440 --> 00:08:58,090
And if you look at the results the KMT lost
heart,

174
00:08:58,090 --> 00:08:59,750
the DPP won overwhelmingly.

175
00:08:59,750 --> 00:09:04,010
A lot of these smaller parties had that space
to grow in the last election,

176
00:09:04,010 --> 00:09:07,010
because people were so confident that the
DPP was going to win.

177
00:09:07,010 --> 00:09:11,550
A lot of voters voted for smaller parties
instead.

178
00:09:11,550 --> 00:09:16,580
Four years later, we have the rise of Han
Kuo-yu.

179
00:09:16,580 --> 00:09:20,760
We have the KMT actually regaining a lot of
their popularity.

180
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:25,050
They're not nearly as unpopular this year
as they were four years ago

